      {
        "id": "14f66f653918538ba5e61236f608b0ca871dca3f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3957,
          "name": "Samuli Silvius",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "s.silvius@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "silvius"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-28 13:44:46.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(3 comments)\n\n> Generic question/doubt: Centos7 is our secondary platform, RedHat\n > being the primary one. Shouldn't we have dockerfile for the latter\n > one in the first place? I mean i'm aware they are sibling platforms\n > but various differences still apply though.\n > \n > Or maybe it is the case that we develop using Centos image and rely\n > on ci/cd with redhat image to be a final verification step before\n > merge? Because if we introduce molecule testing on ONAP's ci/cd\n > then i guess we'll be using this Centos image, not RedHat? What\n > about RedHat OAT then?\n\nYes very correct points, thanks.\n\nThis centos7 Dockerfile is just grapped from internet the first one I found with ssh and systemd pre-installed (reference in the Dockerfile first line) and I think I have not modified it at all.\nSo it's just to get testing ongoing and team (you all) into it to make it better or even better write it all from scratch to exactly meet our purposes and a close as possible to real VM image (for centos6/7 we are going to support).\n\nYes RedHat would be the first one we need. But same as with Centos, I did not had time or skills to write it and especially here would like the team/community to help.\n\nSame with Ubuntu Dockerfile.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "65637d50926e0314af03826e40f86d95f26b8d07",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5097,
          "name": "Bartek Grzybowski",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "b.grzybowski@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "bgrzybowski"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-28 14:06:15.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOk i didn't know it's just a draft taken as is from somewhere else. So if that's the case then we can improve it collaboratively, sure.\n\nBut since we want a container that will resemble a target platform as much as possible, is the Docker the right tool of our choice? Isn't Vagrant what we would really need (with Vbox/Qemu provider)? Or on the other hand in Vagrant the provisioning time would be too long and no way to have fast rollbacks (like with Docker images), correct?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "6fab55e38fb4b349e88c3194aec22fb723d8d29f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3957,
          "name": "Samuli Silvius",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "s.silvius@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "silvius"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-28 16:30:57.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Ok i didn't know it's just a draft taken as is from somewhere else.\n > So if that's the case then we can improve it collaboratively, sure.\n > \n > But since we want a container that will resemble a target platform\n > as much as possible, is the Docker the right tool of our choice?\n > Isn't Vagrant what we would really need (with Vbox/Qemu provider)?\n > Or on the other hand in Vagrant the provisioning time would be too\n > long and no way to have fast rollbacks (like with Docker images),\n > correct?\n\nI think docker is the right one for the testing we intend to do. Like you already answered Vagrant would be just so much heavier that the motivation for developer to develop/run/test on own laptop instead of reserving \"real lab\" (expensive and limited in amounts resource) is too low.\nWith docker driver we can test the functionality very well and leave rest of the integration to real labs (nighly).\nAlso Vagrant driver would require laptop's main operating system to be Linux which usually is not the case but developer runs linux on Virtualbox. Or run it in Windows laptop that surely should work but not so attractive place for our ansible project.\n\n3rd reason is that Vagrant driver is much more in beta level in molecule compared to docker driver.\n\nBut outside of developer testing we surely could setup additional testing pipes in addition to nighly to run same tests with Vagrant driver on CI system at some point.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
